"Based on the passage, I would answer the questions as follows:\n\n***Question 1: \"How likely is it that Bond will escape from Le Chiffre?\"***\n1. Not very likely\n\nBond is trapped, and Le Chiffre has taken away his revolver and comb, which Bond takes pride in using to smooth his hair. Bond also feels \"puny and impotent\", which suggests that he is in a difficult and vulnerable situation.\n\n***Question 2: \"How suspenseful do you find this passage to be?\"***\n6. Very suspenseful\n\nThe passage is suspenseful because it sets up a sense of danger and tension. Bond is caught off guard by the sudden attack, and he is unable to defend himself effectively. The reader is left wondering what will happen to Bond next and whether he will be able to escape from Le Chiffre's clutches. The use of vivid language, such as \"the door burst in toward him\", \"guns drawn\", and \"Bond felt puny and impotent\", adds to the sense of tension and suspense."